    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so it's basically just a way to make sure nobody gets ripped off while things are being finalized. who usually manages the account, is it the lawyer or someone else? also does the money just sit there doing nothing or is it tied to anything specific like property taxes?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It can be both the lawyer or a designated escrow company that manages the account depending on your preference and local practices. The funds do not just sit there; they are held in trust for the buyer and seller until the transfer of the property is finalized. They are generally deposited into the escrow account by the buyer and pulled out once all conditions in the sales contract are met. Property taxes or other specific requirements noted in the contract are often handled separately and accounted for as part of the closing process. The escrow company ensures all necessary disbursements happen correctly and at the appropriate times before funds are released.",
      "source": "target",
